final_output_text: 1. The first step in peeling tomato skins is to bring a pot of water to a rolling boil on the stove top. This is done to create a high-temperature environment that will help loosen the skin of the tomato.

2. Next, a ripe tomato is dropped into either the boiling water (Solution 1) or the ice water (Solution 0) to blanched it. Blanching the tomato in boiling water or ice water serves two purposes: it loosens the skin and inactivates the enzymes that can cause the skin to become bitter. The sudden change in temperature also helps to break down the cell walls, making it easier to remove the skin.

3. Once the skin starts to split at the top of the tomato, it is pulled out of the water and immediately submerged in either the boiling water (Solution 0) or the ice water (Solution 1). This rapid cooling process helps to stop the cooking process and sets the skin, making it easier to remove.

4. Finally, the tomato is then used to peel the skin off using your hands. The loosened skin should come off easily, leaving the tomato ready for use.

